channel.title: Main Method
channel.description:
Hi All,
I'm new to Java, I've got a question about the main method. I've seen couple of people typing up the main method like this:
[code]public static void main (String[] args) { }[/code] and some people do it like this: [code]public static void main (String args[]) { }[/code]
So what is the difference I am wondering, Is it necessary to gave the '[]' after the args or before the args? i try both and in eclipse i get no errors.

[quote=“Davidi2, post:17, topic:528648”][quote author=Taharok link=topic=647401.msg4354656#msg4354656 date=1377282940]
These are equivalent because variadic parameters just converge to an array when compiled.
[/quote]Even before that, yes? Don’t you treat the parameter like an array when referencing it even before compiling?[/quote]

Syntactically yeah, you’re allowed to treat variadic parameters as an array. All I mean is when compiled, variadic paramters do not exist at all. They just render invocation syntax a tad bit easier.

item.title: Main Method
item.dc:creator: @mod_taharok Taharok
item.description:
@mod_taharok wrote:

imthenull:

String [ ] kids [ ] = new String [ 2 ];

Nice try.

There is no difference between [tt]type[] name[/tt] and [tt]type name[][/tt] in most situations. The following is an example where it does make a difference:

int[] anIntArray1, anIntArray2, anIntArray3; // these are all type int[]
int anInt4, anIntArray5[], anInt6; // these mixed types work differently; the first and last are type int, but the middle is int[]

Another aspect is preference as well. For people more familiar or preferred to C/C++, keeping the brackets after the type makes more sense (sort of). It really depends on preference.

As for the main question itself, there is another variety that’s also equivalent. If you’re familiar with variadic parameters:

public static void main(String[] args) {
}

public static void main(String args[]) {
}

public static void main(String... args) {
}

These are equivalent because variadic parameters just converge to an array when compiled.
